# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: unesco
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] The **2011 International Court of Justice election** began on 10 November 2011 at United Nations Headquarters in New York City.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] In the set of triennial elections, the General Assembly and the Security Council concurrently elect five judges to the Court for nine-year terms, in this case beginning on 6 February 2012.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] From the eight candidates, the five winners were Giorgio Gaja (Italy), Hisashi Owada (Japan), Peter Tomka (Slovakia), Xue Hanqin (China) and Julia Sebutinde (Uganda).
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] The International Court of Justice (ICJ), based in The Hague, is one of the principal organs of the United Nations.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Also known as the World Court, it adjudicates legal disputes between states, and provides advisory opinions on legal questions submitted by other UN organs or agencies.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] The court consists of 15 judges, with five judges elected every three years.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] (In the case of death or other vacancy, a judge is elected for the remainder of the term.) Judges are required to be independent and impartial; they may not exercise any political or administrative function, and do not act as a representative of their home state.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Elections of members of the Court are governed by articles 2 through 15 of the Statute of the International Court of Justice.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] The seats of Judges Koroma, Owada, Simma, Tomka and Xue were thus to be contested at the 2011 election.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Of these five, all except Bruno Simma were candidates for re-election.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Another sitting judge, Awn Shawkat Al-Khasawneh, also had left the ICJ, having been appointed prime minister of Jordan in October 2011.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] The election to fill that seat was not scheduled until 2012.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] The General Assembly and the Security Council proceed, independently of one another, to elect five members of the Court.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] To be elected, a candidate must obtain an absolute majority of votes both in the General Assembly and in the Security Council.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] The words "absolute majority" are interpreted as meaning a majority of all electors, whether or not they vote or are allowed to vote.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Thus 97 votes constitute an absolute majority in the General Assembly and 8 votes constitute an absolute majority in the Security Council (with no distinction being made between permanent and non-permanent members of the Security Council).
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Only those candidates whose names appear on the ballot papers are eligible for election.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Each elector in the General Assembly and in the Security Council may vote for not more than five candidates on the first ballot and, on subsequent ballots for five less the number of candidates who have already obtained an absolute majority.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] When five candidates have obtained the required majority in one of the organs, the president of that organ notifies the president of the other organ of the names of the five candidates.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] The president of the latter does not communicate such names to the members of that organ until that organ itself has given five candidates the required majority of votes.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] After both the General Assembly and the Security Council have produced a list of five names that received an absolute majority of the votes, the two lists are compared.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Any candidate appearing on both lists is elected.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] If after the third meeting, one or more seats still remain unfilled, the General Assembly and the Security Council may form a joint conference consisting of six members, three appointed by each organ.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] This joint conference may, by an absolute majority, agree upon one name for each seat still vacant and submit the name for the respective acceptance of the General Assembly and the Security Council.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] If the joint conference is unanimously agreed, it may submit the name of a person not included in the list of nominations, provided that candidate fulfils the required conditions of eligibility to be a judge on the ICJ.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] In the event of a tie vote among the judges, the eldest judge shall have a casting vote.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Nominations of candidates for election to the ICJ are made by individuals who sit on the Permanent Court of Arbitration (PCA).
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] For this purpose, members of the PCA act in "national groups" (i.e. all the PCA members from any individual country).
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Every such "national group" may nominate up to four candidates, not more than two of whom shall be of their own nationality.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Before making these nominations, each "national group" is recommended to consult its highest court of justice, its legal faculties and schools of law, and its national academies and national sections of international academies devoted to the study of law.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] By a communication dated 8 March 2011, the Secretary-General of the United Nations invited the "national groups" to undertake the nomination of persons as judges of the ICJ, and submit the nominations no later than 30 June 2011.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] As in each of the bodies, 5 candidates received an absolute majority of votes, no further rounds of voting were required before comparing the two lists.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Four candidates - Giorgio Gaja, Hisashi Owada, Peter Tomka, and Xue Hanqin - obtained majority support in both bodies and thus were elected Judges.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] In order to fill the fifth slot, both bodies proceeded to further rounds of voting.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Each time that both bodies produced a candidate enjoying majority support, the "lists" (on this occasion, containing one name each) were compared, and in case different candidates were preferred by the Assembly and the Council, technically a new meeting had to begin at each body.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] The General Assembly and the Security Council were deadlocked over the fifth slot, with the General Assembly giving a majority to Julia Sebutinde of Uganda, and the Security Council giving a majority to Abdul Koroma of Sierra Leone.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] After Meeting 3, the statutory possibility opened for the Assembly and the Council to convene a "joint conference" consisting of six members, three appointed by the Assembly and three by the Council, in order to complete the election.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] However, upon proposal of the chairman based on previous practice, the Assembly agreed not to avail itself of this opportunity and voting continued in further meetings.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] During the final vote on that day, Koroma had 9 votes to Sebutinde's 6 in the Security Council, while Sebutinde had 97 votes to Koroma's 96 in the General Assembly.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Balloting for the fifth seat resumed in both organs on 22 November, with three additional rounds of voting in the Security Council and four additional rounds of voting in the General Assembly.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Koroma and Sebutinde were the only two remaining candidates.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] The two organs remained deadlocked, however, with the General Assembly giving an absolute majority to Sebutinde (in three rounds of voting) and the Security Council giving an absolute majority to Koroma.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] On the last round of voting in the General Assembly, the result was 102 votes for Sebutinde and 89 votes for Koroma (with 191 out of 193 members voting).
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] On the last round of voting in the Security Council, the result was 8 votes for Koroma and 7 votes for Sebutinde.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Koroma's name, however, was never withdrawn.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Sierra Leone has never confirmed that it made such an undertaking.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Rather, it continued to support Koroma strongly.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] On 28 November, Uganda's representative at the UN Adonia Ayebare said the Ugandan Mission is working round the clock to ensure a Sebutinde victory.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Balloting resumed in New York City the afternoon of 13 December 2011, and Sebutinde was declared elected after receiving an absolute majority of votes in both the Security Council and the General Assembly.
[src:unesco/2011-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] In 2012, Dalveer Bhandari (India) was elected to fill the remaining vacancy.
[src:unesco/2014-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] The **2014 International Court of Justice election** began on 6 November 2014 at United Nations Headquarters in New York City.
[src:unesco/2014-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] In the set of triennial elections, the General Assembly and the Security Council concurrently elect five judges to the Court for nine-year terms, in this case beginning on 6 February 2015.
[src:unesco/2014-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] The seats of Judges Sepúlveda Amor, Keith, Bennouna, Skotnikov and Donoghue were thus to be contested at the 2014 election.
[src:unesco/2014-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Judges Bennouna and Donoghue stood for re-election, while the other three did not.
[src:unesco/2014-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] The words “absolute majority” are interpreted as meaning a majority of all electors, whether or not they vote or are allowed to vote.
[src:unesco/2014-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] If the joint conference is unanimously agreed, it may submit the name of a person not included in the list of nominations, provided that candidate fulfills the required conditions of eligibility to be a judge on the ICJ.
[src:unesco/2014-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] By a communication dated 31 January 2014, the Secretary-General of the United Nations invited the "national groups" to undertake the nomination of persons as judges of the ICJ, and submit the nominations no later than 30 June 2014.
[src:unesco/2014-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] The Mauritanian delegation withdrew the candidacy of Jemal Agatt prior to the first round of voting.
[src:unesco/2014-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] The Congolese and Madagascan delegations withdrew the candidacies of Sayeman Bula-Bula, and Eugénie Liliane Arivony respectively prior to the fourth round of voting in the General Assembly.
[src:unesco/2014-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Having received majority support in both the General Assembly and the Security Council, Mohamed Bennouna, James Crawford, Joan Donoghue, and Kirill Gevorgian were elected to the Court at the end of the first day of voting.
[src:unesco/2014-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] On Day 1, the Security Council and the General Assembly, independently from one another, each held a meeting in order to select five candidates, and no more, who enjoyed majority support in the respective body.
[src:unesco/2014-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] After the first meeting of each body, four candidates received the absolute majority of votes in both.
[src:unesco/2014-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] On Day 2, the Council and the Assembly proceeded to elect a judge to fill that seat, out of the two candidates who remained in the race.
[src:unesco/2014-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Technically, each time a candidate received majority support in one of the bodies, the respective meeting of that body was over and the two bodies compared results of their votes.
[src:unesco/2014-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] If the same candidate received majority support, he or she would be elected to the Court.
[src:unesco/2014-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] If different candidates received majority support, then each body proceeded to a new vote, technically at a new meeting.
[src:unesco/2014-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] At every meeting, Patrick Lipton Robinson received majority support at the General Assembly, while Susana Ruiz Cerutti received majority support at the Security Council.
[src:unesco/2014-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Due to the impasse, further rounds of voting were postponed in order to allow delegations time for consultations.
[src:unesco/2014-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Prior to the third day of voting the Argentine delegation withdrew the candidacy of Susana Ruiz Cerutti.
[src:unesco/2014-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Patrick Lipton Robinson was thus elected for the last vacant seat at the Court.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-general-assembly-presidential-election] An indirect **presidential election** was held to choose the President of the United Nations General Assembly on 13 June 2016 to replace Mogens Lykketoft and preside over the Seventy-first session of the United Nations General Assembly.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-general-assembly-presidential-election] It was the rotational turn of the Asia-Pacific Group to preside over the session.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-general-assembly-presidential-election] Peter Thomson was elected with 94 votes for and 90 votes against.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-general-assembly-presidential-election] This was the first time since 2012 that there was no consensus candidate from the regional groupings, thus invoking a secret ballot vote.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-general-assembly-presidential-election] Though there is usually a consensus candidate from the rotational group which is scheduled to hold the post of president of the United Nations General Assembly, if there is no consensus candidate then a vote is held by secret ballot amongst the entire United Nations General Assembly.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-general-assembly-presidential-election] The election takes added import as it occurs in a year of the United Nations Secretary-General election.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-general-assembly-presidential-election] The Asia-Pacific Group is the second-largest of the UN regional groups with 53 members who are informally entitled to choose a candidate from within their group.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-general-assembly-presidential-election] Fiji's ran its former ambassador as a candidate.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-general-assembly-presidential-election] Peter Thomson had previously sought citizenship in Australia and New Zealand after a coup in his country but was later re-issued citizenship with a new law and took up the diplomatic posts.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-general-assembly-presidential-election] Cyprus nominated Andreas Mavroyiannis as a candidate.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-general-assembly-presidential-election] He had previously served as negotiator for talks over the Cyprus conflict and was also ambassador to the UN.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-general-assembly-presidential-election] Thomson won narrowly over Mavroyiannis by a vote of 94 to 90 member states, with nine abstentions.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] A United Nations Secretary-General selection was held in October 2016 to choose the ninth secretary-general of the United Nations to succeed Ban Ki-moon from 1 January 2017.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] Six straw polls were held in the Security Council from 21 July 2016 to 5 October 2016.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] António Guterres of Portugal led the polling in every round, finishing the last round with 13 'encourage' votes, 0 'discourage' votes, and 2 abstentions.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] On 6 October 2016, the Security Council unanimously recommended Guterres to the General Assembly, which formally selected him by acclamation on 13 October 2016.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] The 2016 selection was much more open than previous selections, with public nominations being sought and candidates participating in televised debates.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] Women and Eastern Europeans were favoured, as no woman had ever served as secretary-general, and the Eastern European Group was the only one of the UN Regional Groups never to have held the office.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] Article 97 of the United Nations Charter, states "The Secretary-General shall be appointed by the General Assembly upon the recommendation of the Security Council".
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] As a result, the selection is subject to the veto of any of the five permanent members of the Security Council.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] The Charter's minimal language has since been supplemented by other procedural rules and accepted practices.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon would be completing his second term on 31 December 2016, after which he would step down due to the informal two-term limit.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] Under the principle of regional rotation, candidates from Asia were ineligible to succeed Ban.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] As a result, the 2016 selection was the most diverse since 1981.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] Candidates from three regional groups were considered for the position: the Eastern European Group, the Western European and Others Group, and the Latin American and Caribbean Group.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] No woman has ever been selected as secretary-general, and thus in December 2015, General Assembly President Mogens Lykketoft and Security Council President Samantha Power wrote a joint letter to all member states, encouraging them to nominate female candidates as well as men.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] Equality Now launched a campaign to elect a female Secretary-General with the title "Time for a Woman: United Nations—it’s been over 70 years, elect a female Secretary-General".
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] Seven female candidates were nominated in 2016, more than in any previous selection.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] Historically, the process of selecting a secretary-general has been so secretive that it has been compared to a papal conclave.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] Diplomats advanced their own candidacies by lobbying members of the Security Council.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] Straw polls were taken by secret ballot in the Security Council consultation room, and the voting results were not revealed publicly.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] All reported information came in the form of leaks.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] There has been criticism of the opacity of the process.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] Writing in Singapore's *Straits Times*, Simon Chesterman has argued that, for an organisation as important as the United Nations, "having its leader chosen by the lowest common denominator of what the P5 finds acceptable is not good enough".
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] NGOs such as the 1 for 7 Billion campaign and The Elders also favored a more transparent process.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] The Security Council and General Assembly took steps to make the selection process more transparent and open in 2016.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] General Assembly President Mogens Lykketoft and Security Council President Samantha Power sent out a joint letter soliciting candidates from member countries.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] Candidates also participated in televised debates, where they answered questions about their goals.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] When the Security Council met to conduct its first straw poll, it voted in private, as it had done in all selections since 1981.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] The President of the General Assembly was officially informed that a straw poll had been taken, but the results of the poll were not disclosed.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] Lykketoft realized that "the outcome of this and future informal straw polls will not be communicated" and complained that it "does not live up to the expectations of the membership and the new standard of openness and transparency".
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] All further straw polls were also taken in private.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] At the time of the final straw poll on 5 October 2016, there were ten candidates for the post.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] Portugal's former Prime Minister and former United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees António Guterres led in all six straw polls.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] In July 2016, it was revealed that former Labor Prime Minister of Australia Kevin Rudd asked the Government of Australia (then a government of the Liberal/National Coalition) to nominate him for secretary-general in April 2016.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] The Security Council held a series of six straw polls in the consultation room.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] Security Council members were asked to indicate whether they "encouraged", "discouraged" or had "no opinion" regarding the candidates.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] The initial five straw polls took place on 21 July, 5 August, 29 August, 9 September, and 26 September.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] During the sixth straw poll, the five permanent members voted on red-coloured ballots to reveal whether any of them intended to veto a candidate, while the rotating members voted on white ballots.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] Since António Guterres was the only candidate who received the necessary nine *encouraged* votes and had no *discouraged* votes from permanent members, Guterres was declared by the Security Council as the "clear favourite".
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] On 6 October 2016, the Security Council voted by acclamation to recommend António Guterres in Security Council Resolution 2311.
[src:unesco/2016-united-nations-secretary-general-selection] On 13 October 2016, the seventy-first session of the United Nations General Assembly ratified the Security Council's choice by acclamation, formally appointing Guterres as the next Secretary-General for a five-year term beginning on 1 January 2017.
[src:unesco/2017-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] The **2017 International Court of Justice election** took place from 9 to 20 November 2017 at the United Nations Headquarters in New York City.
[src:unesco/2017-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] In the set of triennial elections, the General Assembly and the Security Council concurrently elect five judges to the Court for nine-year terms, in this case beginning on 6 February 2018.
[src:unesco/2017-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] From the seven candidates, the five winners were Abdulqawi Yusuf (Somalia), Antônio Augusto Cançado Trindade (Brazil), Nawaf Salam (Lebanon), Ronny Abraham (France) and Dalveer Bhandari (India).
[src:unesco/2017-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Unusually, all the five judges whose term was to expire, were candidates for re-election.
[src:unesco/2017-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] By a communication dated 1 February 2017, the Secretary-General of the United Nations invited the "national groups" to undertake the nomination of persons as judges of the ICJ, and submit the nominations no later than 3 July 2017.
[src:unesco/2017-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] The first meeting in order to elect judges of the Court was held simultaneously at the General Assembly and the Security Council on 9 November 2017.
[src:unesco/2017-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] The Zambian delegation withdrew the candidacy of Chaloka Beyani prior to the first round of voting.
[src:unesco/2017-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] During the first three rounds of balloting at the Security Council and the first four rounds of balloting at the General Assembly, all six candidates received an absolute majority of votes.
[src:unesco/2017-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Therefore, each body proceeded to further rounds of balloting until only five candidates received majority support.
[src:unesco/2017-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] After each body chose five candidates, the lists were compared, resulting in Ronny Abraham, Antônio Augusto Cançado Trindade, Abdulqawi Ahmed Yusuf and Nawaf Salam being elected to the Court after receiving majority support in both bodies.
[src:unesco/2017-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] The General Assembly and Security Council then proceeded to another meeting in order to fill the fifth vacant seat, choosing between Dalveer Bhandari and Christopher Greenwood.
[src:unesco/2017-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] After the first meeting was inconclusive, the Council and the Assembly convened a second meeting on the same day.
[src:unesco/2017-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] No candidate received the required absolute majorities in both bodies.
[src:unesco/2017-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] After several rounds of voting on 9 November 2017 left one seat vacant, the General Assembly and the Security Council reconvened in order to fill that remaining vacancy, on 13 November 2017.
[src:unesco/2017-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Several rounds of voting were held, each one technically constituting a separate meeting of each body.
[src:unesco/2017-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] After the first round of voting on 13 November, technically the 3rd meeting of these elections, the statutory possibility emerged to convene a joint conference of representatives of the Assembly and the Council; however, no delegation raised the matter during the third or any subsequent meeting.
[src:unesco/2017-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] After several inconclusive rounds of voting on 13 November 2017, the Assembly and the Council postponed the procedure.
[src:unesco/2017-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] They reconvened in order to fill the remaining vacant seat at the Court on 20 November 2017.
[src:unesco/2017-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Prior to the meeting the UK withdrew the candidacy of Christopher Greenwood.
[src:unesco/2017-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Dalveer Bhandari was elected to the last vacant seat.
[src:unesco/2017-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Bhandari's election also upset the tradition of five seats being occupied by the Western European and Others Group and three seats being occupied by the Asia-Pacific Group.
[src:unesco/2017-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Following the election, which was seen as a loss by the UK, the Foreign Affairs Select Committee of the House of Commons of the United Kingdom published a report, containing its conclusions and recommendations to the UK government regarding the election.
[src:unesco/2020-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] The **2020 International Court of Justice election** were held on 11 and 12 November 2020 at the United Nations Headquarters in New York City.
[src:unesco/2020-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] In the set of triennial elections, the General Assembly and the Security Council concurrently elect five judges to the Court for nine-year terms, in this case beginning on 6 February 2021.
[src:unesco/2020-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] In the case of death or other vacancy, a judge is elected for the remainder of the term.
[src:unesco/2020-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Judges are required to be independent and impartial; they may not exercise any political or administrative function, and do not act as a representative of their home state.
[src:unesco/2020-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] The seats of Judges Tomka, Xue, Sebutinde, Gaja and Iwasawa were thus to be contested at the 2020 election.
[src:unesco/2020-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] All but Judge Gaja were nominated for re-election.
[src:unesco/2020-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] All States parties to the Statute of the ICJ have the right to propose candidates.
[src:unesco/2020-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Nominations of candidates for election to the ICJ are made by a group consisting of the members of the Permanent Court of Arbitration (PCA), designated by that State.
[src:unesco/2020-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] For this purpose, members of the PCA act in "national groups" (i.e. all the PCA members from any individual state).
[src:unesco/2020-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] (In the case of UN member states not represented in the PCA, the state in question may select up to four individuals to be its "national group" for the purpose of nominating candidates to the ICJ).
[src:unesco/2020-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] After the established deadline for nominating candidates, 24 June 2020, a national group submitted a nomination to the Secretariat.
[src:unesco/2020-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Eight candidates contested the five positions.
[src:unesco/2020-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] ICJ judges are elected through parallel procedures at the General Assembly and the Security Council.
[src:unesco/2020-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Each of the two bodies, independently from the other, has to determine five persons enjoying support of an absolute majority of its members.
[src:unesco/2020-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Currently, 97 votes constitute an absolute majority in the General Assembly and 8 votes constitute an absolute majority in the Security Council (with no distinction being made between permanent and non-permanent members of the Security Council).
[src:unesco/2020-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] If less than five persons obtain an absolute majority of votes after the first round of balloting, further rounds are held during the same meeting, involving only those candidates that have not obtained an absolute majority of votes.
[src:unesco/2020-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] If more than five persons obtain an absolute majority of votes after the first round of balloting, further rounds are held during the same meeting, involving all candidates, until the number of candidates enjoying an absolute majority of votes, becomes five or less.
[src:unesco/2020-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] According to the ICJ Statute, if after the third meeting, one or more seats still remain unfilled, the General Assembly and the Security Council *may* form a joint conference consisting of six members, three appointed by each organ.
[src:unesco/2020-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] In practice, a joint conference has never been convened.
[src:unesco/2020-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Instead, the Assembly and the Council continued balloting in further meetings until the same candidate received an absolute majority of votes in both bodies (usually after the weaker candidate withdrew).
[src:unesco/2020-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] As more than five candidates received the absolute majority of votes after the first round of voting at the General Assembly, further rounds were required until only five, and no more, obtained an absolute majority.
[src:unesco/2020-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] The Assembly held a second round of voting, still technically being in the same meeting, on 12 November.
[src:unesco/2020-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] After Emmanuel Ugirashebuja received less than 97 votes, only 5 candidates remained with an absolute majority.
[src:unesco/2020-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] The Security Council, meeting independently from but concurrently with the General Assembly, chose five candidates in a single round of voting on 11 November 2020.
[src:unesco/2020-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Since the same five candidates were chosen by the Assembly and the Council, they were thus elected to the Court, without the need of further rounds of voting.
[src:unesco/2021-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] The **2021 International Court of Justice election** was held on 5 November 2021 at the United Nations Headquarters in New York City.
[src:unesco/2021-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] The General Assembly and the Security Council concurrently elected Hilary Charlesworth (Australia) to the International Court of Justice for remainder of the nine-year term of office that had been held by Judge James Crawford (Australia).
[src:unesco/2021-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] In the election, two candidates were vying for the remaining term of one position, opened following the death of Judge Crawford, beginning on 5 November 2021, the date on which they were voted by the Security Council and General Assembly, and ending on 5 February 2024.
[src:unesco/2021-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] The nominated candidates were Hilary Charlesworth (Australia) and Linos‑Alexander Sicilianos (Greece).
[src:unesco/2021-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Charlesworth (Australia) received the required majority in the Security Council, as well as an absolute majority of votes in the General Assembly.
[src:unesco/2021-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Under the terms of the Statute of the ICJ, a candidate obtaining an absolute majority of votes in the General Assembly and the Security Council is considered elected.
[src:unesco/2021-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] In the General Assembly, all 193 Member States in the General Assembly are electors.
[src:unesco/2021-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] Accordingly, for the election, 97 votes constitute an absolute majority in the Assembly.
[src:unesco/2021-international-court-of-justice-judges-election] In the Security Council, eight votes constitute an absolute majority and no distinction is made between its permanent and non‑permanent members.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] The **United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization** (**UNESCO** /juːˈnɛskoʊ/) is a specialized agency of the United Nations (UN) with the aim of promoting world peace and security through international cooperation in education, arts, sciences and culture.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] It has 194 member states and 12 associate members, as well as partners in the non-governmental, intergovernmental and private sector.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] Headquartered in Paris, France, UNESCO has 53 regional field offices and 199 national commissions.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] UNESCO was founded in 1945 as the successor to the League of Nations' International Committee on Intellectual Cooperation.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] UNESCO's founding mission, which was shaped by the events of World War II, is to advance peace, sustainable development and human rights by facilitating collaboration and dialogue among nations.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] It pursues this objective through five major programme areas: education, natural sciences, social/human sciences, culture and communication/information.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] UNESCO sponsors projects that improve literacy, provide technical training and education, advance science, protect independent media and press freedom, preserve regional and cultural history, and promote cultural diversity.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] The organization prominently helps establish and secure World Heritage Sites of cultural and natural importance.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] UNESCO is governed by the General Conference composed of member states and associate members, which meets biannually to set the agency's programmes and budget.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] It also elects members of the executive board, which manages UNESCO's work, and appoints every four years a Director-General, who serves as UNESCO's chief administrator.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] UNESCO and its mandate for international cooperation can be traced to a League of Nations resolution on 21 September 1921, to elect a commission to study the feasibility of having nations freely share cultural, educational and scientific achievements.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] This new body, the International Committee on Intellectual Cooperation (ICIC), was created in 1922 and counted such figures as Henri Bergson, Albert Einstein, Marie Curie, Robert A.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] Millikan, and Gonzague de Reynold among its members (being thus a small commission of the League of Nations essentially centred on Western Europe).
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] The International Institute for Intellectual Cooperation (IIIC) was then created in Paris in September 1924, to act as the executing agency for the ICIC.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] However, the onset of World War II largely interrupted the work of these predecessor organizations.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] As for private initiatives, the International Bureau of Education (IBE) began to work as a non-governmental organization in the service of international educational development since December 1925 and joined UNESCO in 1969, after having established a joint commission in 1952.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] After the signing of the Atlantic Charter and the Declaration of the United Nations, the Conference of Allied Ministers of Education (CAME) began meetings in London which continued from 16 November 1942 to 5 December 1945.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] On 30 October 1943, the necessity for an international organization was expressed in the Moscow Declaration, agreed upon by China, the United Kingdom, the United States and the USSR.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] This was followed by the Dumbarton Oaks Conference proposals of 9 October 1944.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] The idea of UNESCO was largely developed by Rab Butler, the Minister of Education for the United Kingdom, who had a great deal of influence in its development.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] At the ECO/CONF, the Constitution of UNESCO was introduced through Article 57, and signed by 41 countries, and a Preparatory Commission was established.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] The Preparatory Commission operated between 16 November 1945, and 4 November 1946 — the date when UNESCO's Constitution came into force with the deposit of the twentieth ratification by a member state.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] The first General Conference took place from 19 November to 10 December 1946, and elected Julian Huxley to Director-General.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] United States Army colonel, university president and civil rights advocate Blake R.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] The Constitution was amended in November 1954 when the General Conference resolved that members of the executive board would be representatives of the governments of the States of which they are nationals and would not, as before, act in their personal capacity.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] This change in governance distinguished UNESCO from its predecessor, the ICIC, in how member states would work together in the organization's fields of competence.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] As member states worked together over time to realize UNESCO's mandate, political and historical factors have shaped the organization's operations in particular during the Cold War, the decolonization process, and the dissolution of the Soviet Union.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] In 1955, the Republic of South Africa withdrew from UNESCO saying that some of the organization's publications amounted to "interference" in the country's "racial problems".
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] It rejoined the organization in 1994 under the leadership of Nelson Mandela.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] One of the early work of UNESCO in the education field was a pilot project on fundamental education in the Marbial Valley, Haiti, which was launched in 1947.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] Following this project one of expert missions to other countries, included a 1949 mission to Afghanistan.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] UNESCO recommended in 1948 that Member countries should make free primary education compulsory and universal.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] The World Conference on Education for All, in Jomtien, Thailand, started a global movement in 1990 to provide basic education for all children, youths and adults.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] In 2000, World Education Forum in Dakar, Senegal, led member governments to commit for achieving basic education for all in 2015.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] The World Declaration on Higher Education was adopted by UNESCO's World Conference on Higher Education on 9 October 1998, with the aim of setting global standards on the ideals and accessibility of higher education.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] UNESCO's early activities in culture included the International Campaign to Save the Monuments of Nubia, launched in 1960.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] The purpose of the campaign was to move the Great Temple of Abu Simbel to keep it from being swamped by the Nile after the construction of the Aswan Dam.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] During the 20-year campaign, 22 monuments and architectural complexes were relocated.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] This was the first and largest in a series of campaigns including Mohenjo-daro (Pakistan), Fes (Morocco), Kathmandu (Nepal), Borobudur (Indonesia) and the Acropolis of Athens (Greece).
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] The organization's work on heritage led to the adoption, in 1972, of the Convention concerning the Protection of the World Cultural and Natural Heritage.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] In 1976, the World Heritage Committee was established and the first sites were included on the World Heritage List in 1978.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] Since then important legal instruments on cultural heritage and diversity have been adopted by UNESCO member states in 2003 (Convention for the Safeguarding of the Intangible Cultural Heritage) and 2005 (Convention on the Protection and Promotion of the Diversity of Cultural Expressions).
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] An intergovernmental meeting of UNESCO in Paris in December 1951 led to the creation of the European Council for Nuclear Research, which was responsible for establishing the European Organization for Nuclear Research (CERN) later on, in 1954.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] Arid Zone programming, 1948–1966, is another example of an early major UNESCO project in the field of natural sciences.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] In 1968, UNESCO organized the first intergovernmental conference aimed at reconciling the environment and development, a problem that continues to be addressed in the field of sustainable development.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] The main outcome of the 1968 conference was the creation of UNESCO's Man and the Biosphere Programme.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] UNESCO has been credited with the diffusion of national science bureaucracies.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] In the field of communication, the "free flow of ideas by word and image" has been in UNESCO's constitution since it was established, following the experience of the Second World War when control of information was a factor in indoctrinating populations for aggression.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] In the years immediately following World War II, efforts were concentrated on reconstruction and on the identification of needs for means of mass communication around the world.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] UNESCO started organizing training and education for journalists in the 1950s.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] The same year, UNESCO created the International Programme for the Development of Communication (IPDC), a multilateral forum designed to promote media development in developing countries.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] In 1993, UNESCO's General Conference endorsed the Windhoek Declaration on media independence and pluralism, which led the UN General Assembly to declare the date of its adoption, 3 May, as World Press Freedom Day.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] Since 1997, UNESCO has awarded the UNESCO / Guillermo Cano World Press Freedom Prize every 3 May.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] In 2011, UNESCO admitted Palestine as a member.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] Laws had passed in the United States after Palestine applied for UNESCO and WHO membership in April 1989 mean that the United States cannot contribute financially to any UN organization that accepts Palestine as a full member.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] As a result, the United States withdrew its funding, which had accounted for about 22% of UNESCO's budget.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] Israel also reacted to Palestine's admittance to UNESCO by freezing Israeli payments to UNESCO and imposing sanctions on the Palestinian Authority, stating that Palestine's admittance would be detrimental "to potential peace talks".
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] In 2013, two years after stopping payment of its dues to UNESCO, the United States and Israel lost UNESCO voting rights, but without losing the right to be elected; thus, the United States was elected as a member of the executive board for the period from 2016 to 2019.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] Also in 2023, the United States stated its intent to rejoin UNESCO, five years after leaving, and to pay its US$600 million of back dues.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] The United States was readmitted by the UNESCO General Conference that July.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] Three years later, in 2025, however, the United States stated its intent to withdraw again, to be effective as of December 2026.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] In 2023, Russia was not renewed as member of the executive committee for the first time, after failing to get sufficient votes.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] The 2022 MONDIACULT conference was held again in Mexico, and a 2025 edition is planned in Barcelona, Spain.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] UNESCO implements its activities through five programme areas: education, natural sciences, social and human sciences, culture, and communication and information.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] The UNESCO transparency portal has been designed to enable public access to information regarding the Organization's activities, such as its aggregate budget for a biennium, as well as links to relevant programmatic and financial documents.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] These two distinct sets of information are published on the IATI registry, respectively based on the IATI Activity Standard and the IATI Organization Standard.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] Two new UNESCO lists have been proposed.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] The first proposed list would focus on movable cultural heritage such as artifacts, paintings, and biofacts.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] The second proposed list would focus on the world's living species.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] UNESCO and its specialized institutions issue a number of magazines.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] Created in 1945, *The UNESCO Courier* magazine states its mission to "promote UNESCO's ideals, maintain a platform for the dialogue between cultures and provide a forum for international debate".
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] Since March 2006 it has been available free online, with limited printed issues.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] Its articles express the opinions of the authors which are not necessarily the opinions of UNESCO.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] There was a hiatus in publishing between 2012 and 2017.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] In 1950, UNESCO initiated the quarterly review *Impact of Science on Society* (also known as *Impact*) to discuss the influence of science on society.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] UNESCO has official relations with 322 international non-governmental organizations (NGOs).
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] Most of these are what UNESCO calls "operational"; a select few are "formal".
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] The institutes are specialized departments of the organization that support UNESCO's programme, providing specialized support for cluster and national offices.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] As of July 2023, UNESCO has 194 member states and 12 associate members.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] Some members are not independent states and some members have additional National Organizing Committees from some of their dependent territories.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] UNESCO state parties are the United Nations member states (except Israel and Liechtenstein), as well as Cook Islands, Niue and Palestine.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] On 4 May 2025, Nicaragua announced its decision to withdraw from UNESCO, effective 31 December 2026.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] The United States left UNESCO in 1984, rejoined in 2003, left again in 2018, and rejoined in 2023.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] On 22 July 2025, the United States informed the Director-General of its decision to withdraw again, effective 31 December 2026.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] As of June 2023, there have been 12 Directors-General of UNESCO since its inception – nine men and two women.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] The 12 Directors-General of UNESCO have come from seven regions within the organization: West Europe (5), Central America (1), North America (2), West Africa (1), East Asia (1), East Europe (1), Middle East (1).
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] To date, there has been no elected Director-General from the remaining ten regions within UNESCO: Southeast Asia, South Asia, Central and North Asia, North Africa, East Africa, Central Africa, South Africa, Australia-Oceania, and South America.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] Biennial elections are held, with 58 elected representatives holding office for four years.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] The UNESCO headquarters is located at Place de Fontenoy in Paris, France.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] Several architects collaborated on the construction of the headquarters, including Bernard Zehrfuss, Marcel Breuer and Luigi Nervi.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] It includes a *Garden of Peace* which was donated by the Government of Japan.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] This garden was designed by American-Japanese sculptor artist Isamu Noguchi in 1958 and installed by Japanese gardener Toemon Sano.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] In 1994–1995, in memory of the 50th anniversary of UNESCO, a meditation room was built by Tadao Ando.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] UNESCO's field offices across the globe are categorized into four primary office types based upon their function and geographic coverage: cluster offices, national offices, regional bureaus and liaison offices.
[src:unesco/unesco-p01] The following list of all UNESCO Field Offices is organized geographically by UNESCO Region and identifies the members states and associate members of UNESCO which are served by each office.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] UNESCO has been the centre of controversy in the past, particularly in its relationships with the United States, the United Kingdom, Singapore and the former Soviet Union.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] During the 1970s and 1980s, UNESCO's support for a "New World Information and Communication Order" and its MacBride report calling for democratization of the media and more egalitarian access to information was condemned in these countries as attempts to curb freedom of the press.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] UNESCO was perceived as a platform for communists and Third World dictators to attack the West, in contrast to accusations made by the USSR in the late 1940s and early 1950s.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] In 1984, the United States withheld its contributions and withdrew from the organization in protest, followed by the United Kingdom in 1985.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] Singapore withdrew also at the end of 1985, citing rising membership fees.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] Following a change of government in 1997, the UK rejoined.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] The United States rejoined in 2003, followed by Singapore on 8 October 2007.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] UNESCO has been criticized as being used by the People's Republic of China to present a Chinese Communist Party version of history and to dilute the contributions of ethnic minorities in China such as Uyghurs and Tibetans.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] Israel was admitted to UNESCO in 1949, one year after its creation.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] Israel has maintained its membership since then.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] In 2010, Israel designated the Cave of the Patriarchs in Hebron and Rachel's Tomb in Bethlehem – both in the West Bank – as National Heritage Sites and announced restoration work, prompting criticism from the Obama administration and protests from Palestinians.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] UNESCO described the sites as significant to "people of the Muslim, Christian and Jewish traditions", and accused Israel of highlighting only the Jewish character of the sites.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] Israel in turn accused UNESCO of "detach[ing] the Nation of Israel from its heritage", and accused it of being politically motivated.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] The Rabbi of the Western Wall said that Rachel's tomb had not previously been declared a holy Muslim site.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] Israel partially suspended ties with UNESCO.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] Israeli Deputy Foreign Minister Danny Ayalon declared that the resolution was a "part of Palestinian escalation".
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] Zevulun Orlev, chairman of the Knesset Education and Culture Committee, referred to the resolutions as an attempt to undermine the mission of UNESCO as a scientific and cultural organization that promotes cooperation throughout the world.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] On 28 June 2011, UNESCO's World Heritage Committee, at Jordan's insistence, censured Israel's decision to demolish and rebuild the Mughrabi Gate Bridge in Jerusalem for safety reasons.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] Israel stated that Jordan had signed an agreement with Israel stipulating that the existing bridge must be dismantled for safety reasons; Jordan disputed the agreement, saying that it was only signed under U.S. pressure.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] Israel was also unable to address the UNESCO committee over objections from Egypt.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] The event was scheduled to run from 21 January through 30 January in Paris.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] Bokova cancelled the event after representatives of Arab states at UNESCO argued that its display would "harm the peace process".
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] UNESCO amended the decision to cancel the exhibit within the year, and it quickly achieved popularity and was viewed as a great success.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] On 1 January 2019, Israel formally left UNESCO in pursuance of the US withdrawal over perceived continuous anti-Israel bias.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] On 13 October 2016, UNESCO passed a resolution on East Jerusalem that condemned Israel for "aggressions" by Israeli police and soldiers and "illegal measures" against the freedom of worship and Muslims' access to their holy sites, while also recognizing Israel as the occupying power.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] Palestinian leaders welcomed the decision.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] While the text acknowledged the "importance of the Old City of Jerusalem and its walls for the three monotheistic religions", it referred to the sacred hilltop compound in Jerusalem's Old City only by its Muslim name "Al-Haram al-Sharif", Arabic for Noble Sanctuary.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] In response, Israel denounced the UNESCO resolution for its omission of the words "Temple Mount" or "Har HaBayit", stating that it denies Jewish ties to the key holy site.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] After receiving criticism from numerous Israeli politicians and diplomats, including Benjamin Netanyahu and Ayelet Shaked, Israel froze all ties with the organization.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] On 26 October, UNESCO approved a reviewed version of the resolution, which also criticized Israel for its continuous "refusal to let the body's experts access Jerusalem's holy sites to determine their conservation status".
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] Despite containing some softening of language following Israeli protests over a previous version, Israel continued to denounce the text.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] The resolution refers to the site Jews and Christians refer to as the Temple Mount, or Har HaBayit in Hebrew, only by its Arab name – a significant semantic decision also adopted by UNESCO's executive board, triggering condemnation from Israel and its allies.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] Ambassador Crystal Nix Hines stated: "This item should have been defeated.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] In October 2017, the United States and Israel announced they would withdraw from the organization, citing in-part anti-Israel bias.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] In February 2011, an article was published in a Palestinian youth magazine in which a teenage girl described one of her four role models as Adolf Hitler.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] In December 2011, UNESCO, which partly funded the magazine, condemned the material and subsequently withdrew support.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] In 2012, UNESCO decided to establish a chair at the Islamic University of Gaza in the field of astronomy, astrophysics, and space sciences, fueling controversy and criticism.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] Israel bombed the school in 2008 stating that they develop and store weapons there, which Israel restated in criticizing UNESCO's move.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] The head, Kamalain Shaath, defended UNESCO, stating that "the Islamic University is a purely academic university that is interested only in education and its development".
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] Israeli ambassador to UNESCO Nimrod Barkan planned to submit a letter of protest with information about the university's ties to Hamas, especially angry that this was the first Palestinian university that UNESCO chose to cooperate with.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] He never provided any evidence to support his claim of ties to Hamas.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] The Jewish organization B'nai B'rith criticized the move as well.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] In 2015, Japan threatened to halt funding of UNESCO because of the organization's decision to include documents related to the 1937 Nanjing massacre in the latest listing for its "Memory of the World" program.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] In October 2016, Japanese Foreign Minister Fumio Kishida confirmed that Japan's 2016 annual funding of ¥4.4 billion had been suspended, although he denied any direct link with the Nanjing document controversy.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] Leach concluded that the record showed Israel bashing, a call for a new world information order, money management, and arms control policy to be the impetuses behind the withdrawal; he asserted that before departing from UNESCO, a withdrawal from the IAEA had been pushed on him.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] On 1 October 2003, the United States rejoined UNESCO.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] On 12 October 2017, the United States notified UNESCO it would again withdraw from the organization, on 31 December 2018; Israel followed suit.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] The Department of State cited "mounting arrears at UNESCO, the need for fundamental reform in the organization, and continuing anti-Israel bias at UNESCO".
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] The United States has not paid over $600 million in dues since it stopped paying its $80 million annual UNESCO dues when Palestine became a full member in 2011.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] Israel and the United States were among the 14 votes against the membership out of 194 member countries.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] When the United States announced it was rejoining the body in 2023, it also pledged to pay all past-due payments.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] On 4 February 2025, the White House said to conduct a review of US membership in UNESCO.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] On 22 July, Donald Trump decided that US will again withdraw from UNESCO, effective at the end of 2026.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] On 25 May 2016, Turkish poet and human rights activist Zülfü Livaneli resigned as Turkey's only UNESCO goodwill ambassador.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] He highlighted the human rights situation in Turkey and the destruction of the historical Sur district of Diyarbakir, the largest city in Kurdish-majority southeast Turkey, during fighting between the Turkish army and Kurdish militants as the main reasons for his resignation.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] In 2020 UNESCO stated that the size of the illicit trade in cultural property amounted to 10 billion dollars a year.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] A report that same year by the Rand Organization suggested the actual market is "not likely to be larger than a few hundred million dollars each year".
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] An expert cited by UNESCO as attributing the 10 billion figure denied it, saying he had "no idea" where the figure came from.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] Art dealers were particularly critical of the UNESCO figure because it amounted to 15% of the total world art market.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] In November 2020, part of a UNESCO advertising campaign intended to highlight international trafficking in looted artefacts had to be withdrawn after it falsely presented a series of museum-held artworks with known provenances as recently looted objects held in private collections.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] After complaints by the Met, the adverts were withdrawn.
[src:unesco/unesco-p02] UNESCO develops, maintains, and disseminates, free of charge, two interrelated software packages for database management (CDS/ISIS [not to be confused with UK police software package ISIS]) and data mining/statistical analysis (IDAMS).
